Observation¶

Total Charge column contains string value instead of float. We need to check what is the problem in TotalCharges and impute the value.¶

Customer id contains unique value.¶

MultipleLines, OnlineSecurity,OnlineBackup, DeviceProtection, TechSupport, StreamingTV, there are 3 distinct values i.e "YES", "No" and "No Internet Service". "No" and "No Internet service" are representing same value. So we can change the "No Internet service" as no in the upcoming steps.¶

C. Create a function that will accept a DataFrame as input and return pie-charts for all the appropriate Categorical features. Clearly show percentage distribution in the pie-chart.

In [21]:
import math as math
def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        total = sum(values)
        val = int(round(pct*total/100.0))
        return '{p:.2f}%  ({v:d})'.format(p=pct,v=val)
    return my_autopct
def plotpieChart(df):
    cat_df = df.select_dtypes(include=["object"])
    for column in cat_df.columns:
        fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,3))
        ax1 = fig.add_subplot(121)
        data = cat_df.groupby(column).size()
        data.plot(kind='pie',textprops={'fontsize': 10},
                                           autopct=lambda p: '{:.2f}%({:.0f})'.format(p,(p/100)*data.sum()), shadow=True)
        ax1.set_xlabel(column, size=22)
        ax1.set_ylabel('')
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

E. Encode all the appropriate Categorical features with the best suitable approach.

Replacing No internet service with No. As both are representing the same meaning¶

In [26]:
replace_cols = [ 'OnlineSecurity', 'OnlineBackup', 'DeviceProtection','TechSupport','StreamingTV', 'StreamingMovies']
for i in replace_cols : 
    churn_df[i]  = churn_df[i].replace({'No internet service' : 'No'})

Convert catagorical featuren to number using label encoder. Since machine only understand numbers¶

Here we use labelEncoding for converting all categorical feature to number. IN part B, both one hot encoding and label encoding is used,¶

In [27]:
mapping = {}
labelEncoder = LabelEncoder();
def encode_catagorical_column(df):

    for column in df.select_dtypes(include=['object']):
        labelEncoder.fit(df[column])
        le_name_mapping = dict(zip(labelEncoder.classes_, labelEncoder.transform(labelEncoder.classes_)))
        mapping = dict(zip(column, le_name_mapping)) 
        df[column]=labelEncoder.transform(df[column])
In [28]:
encode_catagorical_column(churn_df)

norm.transform(X_train_norm[numerical_columns])
X_train_norm[numerical_columns] = norm.transform(X_train_norm[numerical_columns])
X_test_norm[numerical_columns] = norm.transform(X_test[numerical_columns])

In [36]:
def printConfusionMetric(y_test, y_pre, labels):
    '''
    This method help user to print the confusion metrics . 
    param 1: Accept the y actual output
    param 2: Predicted outcome from the model
    Return : None
    '''
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pre, labels=labels)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn  No']],
                  columns = ["Predict "+ str(i) for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']])
    plt.figure(figsize = (7,5));
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Label')
    plt.ylabel('Actual Label')
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='g');
In [37]:
def fit_n_print(model, X_train_p, X_test_p, y_train, y_test):  # take the model, train data and test data as input
    '''
    This method accept the model and train, test data.
    This method do  the accuracy, AUC, Cross Validation and return the response. This method perform 3 Cross validation.
    Param 1: It accept the model
    Param 2: X_train is the training data
    Param 3: X_test_p is the testing data
    Param 4: y_train_p is the y variable of training data
    Param 5: y_test is the y variable of training data
    '''
    start = time.time()  # note the start time 
    if isinstance(model, XGBClassifier) :
        model.fit(X_train_p, y_train, early_stopping_rounds=5, eval_set=[(X_test_p, y_test)], eval_metric='auc')   # fit the model using the train data
    else:
        model.fit(X_train_p, y_train);

    pred = model.predict(X_test_p)     # model predictions on the test data
    accuracy_train = model.score(X_train_p, y_train)# calculate the accuracy on the train data
    #print(y_test)
    accuracy_test = model.score(X_test_p, y_test)  # calculate the accuracy on the test data
    
    
    precision = metrics.precision_score(y_test, pred)
    recall = metrics.recall_score(y_test, pred)
    auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, pred)
    scorer = {'accuracy' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.accuracy_score),
              'precision' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.precision_score),
              'recall' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score),
              'f1' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score),
               }    # make scorers to be used in cross validation
    
    cv = cross_validate(model, X_train_p, y_train, cv=cv_value, scoring = scorer, n_jobs=-1)   # perform cross validation accross 4 metrics
    
    accuracy_cv = cv['test_accuracy'].mean()  
    precision_cv =  cv['test_precision'].mean() 
    recall_cv =  cv['test_recall'].mean() 
    f1_cv =  cv['test_f1'].mean() 
    labels = [1,0]
    printConfusionMetric(y_test, pred, labels)
    end = time.time()  #note the end time
    
    
    duration = end - start  # calculate the total duration
    
    
    return accuracy_train, accuracy_test,auc, precision, recall, accuracy_cv, precision_cv, recall_cv, f1_cv, duration,pred
In [38]:
def printResult(result):
    '''
    This method will print score in the form of table. It accept the dictionary object which has all the scores
    Param: result
    return Dataframe coming out from result
    '''
    result1 = pd.DataFrame(np.array(list(result.values()))[:,:-1],    # make a dataframe out of the metrics from result dictionary 
                       columns= ['Training accuracy','Tesing accuracy ', 'auc','precision', 'recall', 'accuracy_cv', 'precision_cv', 'recall_cv', 'f1_cv', 'Elapsed'],
                      index= result.keys())   # use the model names as index

    result1.index.name = 'Model'   # name the index of the result1 dataframe as 'Model'

    return result1
In [39]:
def compareConfusionMatrix(modelName, y_test, y_pre_org, y_pre_norm, y_pre_std, labels):
    fig,axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(15,4))
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pre_org, labels=labels)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']],
                  columns = ["Predict "+ str(i) for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']])
    axs[0].set_title('CM for '+ modelName + ' orgnl Dataset')
    axs[0].set_xlabel('Predicted')
    axs[0].set_ylabel('Original')
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='g',ax=axs[0]);
    
    
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pre_norm, labels=labels)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']],
                  columns = ["Predict "+ str(i) for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']])
    #plt.figure(figsize = (7,5))
    axs[1].set_xlabel('Predicted')
    axs[1].set_ylabel('Original')
    axs[1].set_title('CM for '+ modelName + ' Normalize Dataset')
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='g',ax=axs[1])
    
    
   
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pre_std, labels=labels)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']],
                  columns = ["Predict "+ str(i) for i in ['Churn Yes', 'Churn No']])
    #plt.figure(figsize = (7,5));
    axs[2].set_xlabel('Predicted')
    axs[2].set_ylabel('Original')
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='g',ax=axs[2]);
    axs[2].set_title('CM for '+ modelName + ' Standardize Dataset');

In [43]:
def report_best_scores(results, n_top=3):
    ''' This method print the top rank parameter and model.
    If more than 1  parameter is giving same accuracy, then it will print all the parameters. By default it will print top 3 model
    param 1: results contains resultset of cross validation
    '''
    for i in range(1, n_top + 1):
        candidates = np.flatnonzero(results['rank_test_score'] == i)
        for candidate in candidates:
            print("Model with rank: {0}".format(i))
            print("Mean validation score: {0:.3f} (std: {1:.3f})".format(
                  results['mean_test_score'][candidate],
                  results['std_test_score'][candidate]))
            print("Parameters: {0}".format(results['params'][candidate]))
            print("")
In [44]:
def report_randomiseSearchCV(model, model_params, X_train, y_train,X_test,y_test):
    '''
    This method is used to hyper tune the parameters. This method the train dataset and do the CV. 
    3 cross validation is used in this casestudy. n_jobs=-1 represent it use all the cores available. It enhace the processing.
    Param 1: Accept the mode;
    Param 2: Accept the model parameter
    Param 3: Accept the X train dataset
    Param 4: Accept the y train dataset
    '''
    fit_params={"early_stopping_rounds":20, 
            "eval_metric" : 'auc', 
            "eval_set" : [(X_test,y_test)]
               }
    search = RandomizedSearchCV(model, param_distributions=model_params, random_state=42, n_iter=200, cv=cv_value, verbose=1, n_jobs=-1,refit=True, return_train_score=True, scoring='roc_auc')
    if (isinstance(model, LGBMClassifier) or isinstance(model, XGBClassifier)):
        search.fit(X_train, y_train, **fit_params)
    else:
        search.fit(X_train, y_train)

    report_best_scores(search.cv_results_, 1)
    print(search.best_estimator_)
    return search.best_estimator_

DataSet is imbalance.¶

Testing accuracy of tuned and non tuned models are almost same. AUC score of "TuningModel-with-original-dataset " has been decreased . AUC score of Normalized dataset/ Standardize data set is almost same.¶

B. Improve performance of the XGBoost as much as possible. Also print best performing parameters along with train and test performance.

Since dataset is imbalance. We need to find the weight and again perform the hypertuning.¶

In [54]:
weight= churn_df.Churn.value_counts()[0]/churn_df.Churn.value_counts()[1]
weight
Out[54]:
2.7683253076511503

PART B¶

DOMAIN: IT CONTEXT: The purpose is to build a machine learning workflow that will work autonomously irrespective of Data and users can save efforts involved in building workflows for each dataset. PROJECT OBJECTIVE: Build a machine learning workflow that will run autonomously with the csv file and return best performing model.

1 Build a simple ML workflow which will accept a single ‘.csv’ file as input and return a trained base model that can be used for predictions. You can use1 Dataset from Part 1 (single/merged).¶

2. Create separate functions for various purposes.¶

To achieve the above functionality. We need to create multiple method and create one main method name workflow. Workflow method have many method inside it which is doing data exploration, data cleaning, visualization, model cleaning.¶

In [65]:
def replaceMissingValueWithNull(df):
    """
    replaceMissingValueWithNull iterate each column and check for null value.
    It also check where user add two or more spaces. If yes, then it will replace that spaces with null value.

    :param p1: accept a dataframe 
    :return: it return true or false. It true, then missing value is present.
    """
    isColumnContainMissingValue = False 
    catagorical_col = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
    for column in  catagorical_col:
        if (len(df[df[column].astype(str).str.fullmatch(r"\s*")])):
            df[column] = np.where(df[column].astype(str).str.fullmatch(r"\s*"),np.nan,df[column])
            print('Missing value is found for column : ', column)
            isColumnContainMissingValue = True;
    return isColumnContainMissingValue, df;
In [66]:
def findAndReplaceMissingValue(df):
    """
    findAndReplaceMissingValue does check for missing value. If the missing value is present, then return true.
    It also check where user add two or more spaces. If yes, then it will replace that spaces with null value.

    :param p1: accept a dataframe 
    :return: it return Updated dataframe.
    """ 
    if df.isna().any().any():
        isMissingValueFound , df = replaceMissingValueWithNull(df)
        print('Missing value is found in dataframe')
    else:
        isMissingValueFound , df = replaceMissingValueWithNull(df);
        if not isMissingValueFound:
            print('No missing value found in dataset')
    return df

In [70]:
def imputeMissingValue(df, column, strategy):
    """
    Cover the missing value by mean/Mode/Median. It also validate the column and strategy

    :param p1: accept a dataframe 
    :return: updated dataframe.
    """
    allowedStrategy = ['mean', 'median', 'mode']
    if column in df.columns:
        if strategy in allowedStrategy:
            if strategy == 'mean':
                df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].mean());
                print('Missing data is replaced with mean value')
            if strategy == 'median':
                df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].median());
                print('Missing data is replaced with median value')
            if strategy == 'mode':
                df[column] = df[column].fillna(df[column].mode());
                print('Missing data is replaced with Mode value')
        else:
            print('Strategy is not present in allowed strategy list.Please provide the correct value. The allowed strategy list is ' , allowedStrategy)
    else:
        print(column , ' is not present in dataframe. Please check')
    return df;

def find_and_drop_duplicateRecords(df):
    """
    Check for duplicate value and remove duplicates

    :param p1: accept a dataframe 
    :return: return updated dataframe.
    """    
    if is_duplicate_rows_present(df):
        df.drop_duplicates(inplace=True)
        print('Duplicate Records have been removed')
    else:
        print('No Duplicate Records present')
    return df;

In [78]:
def convertDataType(df, column, dtype):
    """
    Convert the dataframe column dtype

    :param p1: accept a dataframe 
    :param p1: accept a column 
    :param p1: convert dtype 
    :return: updated df.
    """      
    allowed_dtypes = ['object','int64', 'float64', 'bool', 'datetime64', 'category']
    if dtype not in allowed_dtypes:
        print(dtype , ' is not present in allowed list. Please check it')
        raise Exception(dtype , ' is not present in allowed list. Please check it')
    if column not in df.columns:
        raise Exception(column , ' is not present in dataset. Please check it')
    df[column] = df[column].astype(dtype)
    print('dtype of ', column , ' has been changed to ', dtype)
    return df;
In [79]:
def scaleDataSet(Scaler, X_train, y_train, numerical_columns):
    """
    It uses the scaler and data into the desired scaler

    param p1: accept a Scaler 
    param p2: accept a X_train 
    param p3: accept a  y_train 
    Param p4: accept the numerical_columns
    :return: updated df.
    """  
    X_train_scale = X_train.copy()
    X_test_scale = X_test.copy()
    scaler = Scaler.fit(X_train[numerical_columns])
    X_train_scale[numerical_columns] = scaler.transform(X_train_scale[numerical_columns])
    X_test_scale[numerical_columns] = scaler.transform(X_test_scale[numerical_columns])
    print('Successfully Scale the dataset using ', type(Scaler))
    return X_train_scale, X_test_scale
In [80]:
def plt_hist(df, target, excluded_columns=[]):
    '''
    It will display the histogram . User has to provide the target column and excluded column.
    Param 1: dataframe
    Param 2: target column
    Param 3: Excluded column list
    '''
    if not excluded_columns:
        total_column = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
    else:
        total_column = df.drop(excluded_columns, axis=1).select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
    N = len(total_column)
    cols =3;
    rows = int(math.ceil(N/cols))
    fig,axs = plt.subplots(nrows=rows, ncols=cols, figsize=(20,10))
    axs = axs.flatten()
    for ax in axs:
        ax.set_axis_off()
    for i, column in enumerate(total_column):
        if column != target or (not excluded_columns and column not in excluded_columns):
            sns.countplot( x=column, hue=target, data=df, ax=axs[i])
            axs[i].set_axis_on()
            axs[i].set_title(column+" hist plot")
    plt.show()
In [81]:
def plotBox(df, x, y):
    N = len(y)
    cols =2;
    rows = int(math.ceil(N/cols))
    fig,axs = plt.subplots(nrows=rows, ncols=cols, figsize=(15,10))
    axs = axs.flatten()
    for i, ax in enumerate(axs):
        ax.set_axis_off()
    for i, column in enumerate(y):
        sns.boxplot(data=df, x=x, y=column,ax = axs[i]);
        title = (column+ "-" + x + " plot");
        axs[i].set_title(title)
        axs[i].set_axis_on()
    plt.show()
In [82]:
def make_autopct(values):
    def my_autopct(pct):
        total = sum(values)
        val = int(round(pct*total/100.0))
        return '{p:.2f}%  ({v:d})'.format(p=pct,v=val)
    return my_autopct
In [83]:
def plotpieChart(df):
    cat_df = df.select_dtypes(include=["object"])
    N = len(cat_df.columns)
    cols =2;
    rows = int(math.ceil(N/cols))
    fig,axs = plt.subplots(nrows=rows, ncols=cols, figsize=(15,10))
    axs = axs.flatten()
    print(N , cols, rows)
    for i, ax in enumerate(axs):
        ax.set_axis_off()
    for i, column in enumerate(cat_df.columns):
        data = cat_df.groupby(column).size()
        data.plot(kind='pie',textprops={'fontsize': 10},
                                           autopct=lambda p: '{:.2f}%({:.0f})'.format(p,(p/100)*data.sum()), shadow=True)
        ax[i].set_xlabel(column, size=22)
        ax[i].set_ylabel('')
        axs[i].set_axis_on()
        plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def printConfusionMetric(y_test, y_pre, labels):
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pre, labels=labels)
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in labels],
                  columns = ["Predict "+ str(i) for i in labels])
    plt.figure(figsize = (7,5));
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=True, fmt='g');

def dropcolumn(df, column):
    '''
    This method remove the column from the datafram
    Param1 : Contain the dataframe
    Param2 : Contain the column nme which user want to remove
    '''
    if column in df.columns:
        df.drop(column, axis=1 ,inplace=True)
        print(column , ' has been dropped successfully')
    else:
        print(column, ' is not found in dataset. Please check the column name');
    return df
In [87]:
def replaceColumnValue(df, column , fromvalue, to_value):
    '''
    This method replace the column value.
    Param 1 : accppt the dataframe object
    Param2 : Contain the column in which value to be replaced
    Param3 : From value which need to be replaced
    Param4: to value which is used to replace the value
    '''
    df[column]  = df[column].replace({fromvalue : to_value})
    print(fromvalue+ 'has been replaced successfully with '+ to_value+ ' in column '+ column)
    return df;

def pre_processing(df):
    print('----------------------------------PRINT DESCRIBE START---------------------------------------------')
    describe(df)
    print('----------------------------------PRINT DESCRIBE END---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('----------------------------------Find AND REPLACE MISSING VALUE START---------------------------------------------')
    df = findAndReplaceMissingValue(df)
    print('----------------------------------Find AND REPLACE MISSING VALUE END------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('---------------------------------FIND MISSING ROW START-------------------------------------')
    find_missing_row_values(df)
    print('---------------------------------FIND MISSING ROW END---------------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('---------------------------------PRINT COLUMN WISE MISSING VALUE START----------------------------------------')
    find_column_missing_value(df)
    print('---------------------------------PRINT COLUMN WISE MISSING VALUE END------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('--------------------------------REMOVE NULL RECORD START-------------------------------------')
    df = removeNull(df)
    print('--------------------------------REMOVE NULL RECORD END--------------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('--------------------------------FIND AND DROP DUPLICATE ROWS START---------------------------------------------')
    df = find_and_drop_duplicateRecords(df)
    print('--------------------------------FIND AND DROP DUPLICATE ROWS END----------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('---------------------------------Checking COlumn wise Missing value again Start----------------------------------------')
    find_column_missing_value(df)
    print('---------------------------------Checking COlumn wise Missing value again END------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('-------------------------------PRINT UNIQUE VALUES OF EACH COLUMN START-----------------------------------------')
    printUniqueValues(df)
    print('-------------------------------PRINT UNIQUE VALUES OF EACH COLUMN END-----------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('--------------------------------Impute Missing Values START---------------------------------------------')
    df = imputeMissingValue(df, 'TotalCharges', 'median')
    print('-------------------------------Impute Missing Values END-----------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('--------------------------------Convert DataTypes START---------------------------------------------')
    df = convertDataType(df, 'MonthlyCharges', 'float64')
    df = convertDataType(df, 'TotalCharges', 'float64')
    print('--------------------------------Convert DataTypes END---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('--------------------------------Remove Unneed columns START---------------------------------------------')
    df = dropcolumn(df, 'customerID')
    print('--------------------------------Remove Unneed columnsConvert DataTypes END---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('--------------------------------Replacing Columns Value START---------------------------------------------')
    replace_cols = [ 'OnlineSecurity', 'OnlineBackup', 'DeviceProtection','TechSupport','StreamingTV', 'StreamingMovies']
    for column in replace_cols :
        df = replaceColumnValue(df, column, 'No internet service', 'No')
    print('--------------------------------Replacing Columns Value END---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    return df

def oneHotEncoding(df, columns):
    '''This method do one hot encoding 
    Param 1: dataframe
    Param2 : List of columns value in which one hot encoding to be used.
    '''
    print('Performing One hot encoding in columns ', columns)
    df = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=columns, drop_first=True)
    return df;
In [91]:
def performing_label_encoding(df, columns):
    '''This method do label encoding 
    Param 1: dataframe
    Param2 : List of columns value in which label encoding to be used.
    '''
    labelEncoder = LabelEncoder()
    for column  in columns:
        df[column]=labelEncoder.fit_transform(df[column])
    return df;

X_train=X_test=y_train=y_test= None
def performTrainTestSplit(df, targetColumn, test_size=0.20):
    '''Split the dataset into train and test
    Param1 : Accept the dataframe
    Param2: target column name
    Param3: test size. By default it is 20%
    '''
    global X_train,X_test, y_train, y_test;
    X = churn_df.drop(targetColumn,axis=1)
    y = churn_df[[targetColumn]]
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=1, stratify=y)
    print('Successfully spliting the test dataset into ', test_size)
    return X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test;

def data_modeling(df):
    global X_train_norm, X_test_norm,X_train_std, X_test_std;
    print('----------------------------------One Hot Encoding START---------------------------------------------')
    df = oneHotEncoding(df, columns= ['gender', 'Partner', 'Dependents', 'PhoneService', 'MultipleLines', 'InternetService', 'OnlineSecurity', 'OnlineBackup', 'DeviceProtection', 'TechSupport', 'StreamingTV', 'StreamingMovies', 'PaperlessBilling', 'PaymentMethod'])
    print('----------------------------------One Hot Encoding End---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('----------------------------------Label Encoding START---------------------------------------------')
    df = performing_label_encoding(df, columns= ['Contract', 'Churn'])
    print('----------------------------------Label Encoding End---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('----------------------------------Split Train_test START---------------------------------------------')
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = performTrainTestSplit(df, 'Churn', test_size=0.20)
    print('----------------------------------Split Train_test End---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('----------------------------------Normaization/Standardization START---------------------------------------------')
    columns = X_train.columns
    numerical_columns = ['tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']
    X_train_norm, X_test_norm = scaleDataSet(MinMaxScaler(), X_train, y_train, numerical_columns)
    X_train_std, X_test_std = scaleDataSet(StandardScaler(), X_train, y_train, numerical_columns)
    
    print('----------------------------------Normaization/Standardization End---------------------------------------------')
    print('')
    print('')
    print('----------------------------------Prepare A XGBoost START---------------------------------------------')
    xgBoost = xgb.XGBClassifier(random_state=1)
    fit_n_print(model,X_train, X_test,y_train, y_test)
    print('----------------------------------Prepare A XGBoost END---------------------------------------------')
    return xgBoost;

lc = LogisticRegression(random_state=1)
svc = SVC(random_state=1)        
dt = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)   
bc = BaggingClassifier(random_state=1)
rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1, n_estimators=100)  # specifying n_estimators to avoid "future warnings"
gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=1, n_estimators=100)
xgBoost = xgb.XGBClassifier(random_state=1)
catBoostClfr =  CatBoostClassifier(random_state=1)
lbmclfr = LGBMClassifier(random_state=1)
knn = KNeighborsClassifier()
def calculateAccuracy(X_train, X_test,y_train, y_test):
    result={}
    for model, name  in zip([lc, svc, dt, bc, rf, gb, xgBoost, catBoostClfr, lbmclfr, knn], ['Logistic Classifier','SVM Classifier', 'Decision Tree',
                                                         'Bagging Ensemble', 'Random Forest', 'Gradient Boost Ensemble', 'XGBoost', 'CatBoostClassifier', 'LGBMClassifier', 'KNNClassifier']):
        result[name] = fit_n_print(model,X_train, X_test,y_train, y_test)
    return result

In [111]:
result_hypertune= {}
for model, name  in zip([lc,svc, dt, rf, gb, xgBoost, lbmclfr, knn], ['Logistic Classifier','SVM Classifier', 'Decision Tree',
                                                      'Random Forest', 'Gradient Boost Ensemble', 'XGBoost', 'LGBMClassifier', 'KNNClassifier']):
    print('-------------------------------------------------------------')
    print('Hypertuning is performing for model start', name)
    print('-------------------------------------------------------------')
    model = report_randomiseSearchCV(model, params[name], X_train_balance, y_train_balance, X_test_norm, y_test)
    result_hypertune[name+'_Balance_DataSet'] = fit_n_print(model,X_train_balance, X_test_norm,y_train_balance , y_test)
    print('-------------------------------------------------------------')
    print('Hypertuning is performing for model end', name)
    print('-------------------------------------------------------------')

RandomForest, LGBMClassfier , Graident Booster Are giving higer accuracy¶

Gradient Boost is giving highest testing accuracy but taking 28 seconds but recall is not good¶

Logistic and LGBMClassifier is giving better testing accuracy as well as better AUC score and it is taking less time¶

XGBoost Classifier is giving 73% Accuracy , and highest AUC score . It is also giving 81% recall. The time taken to calculate the prediction is also good of XGBoost.¶

Hence XGBoost is the best estimator for the problem¶

4. Pickle file should be saved for the best performing model.¶

saving the XGBoost classifier into the finalized_model.sav file.¶

In [122]:
def writeModelToFile(model, fileName):
    '''
    writeModelToFile is used to save the model to File
    Param 1: Accept the model which need to be saved
    Param 2: Accept the file Name where the model has to be saved.
    '''
    pickle.dump(model, open(filename, 'wb'))
    print('Model saved successfully')
def loadModelFromFile(fileName):
    '''
    loadModelFromFile is used to read the model from File
    Param 1: Accept the file Name where the model has to be read.
    '''
    model = pickle.load(open(filename, 'rb'))
    return model;

Saving the mode into file¶
